df-no
blocks.content: Define the class of surreal numbers. The surreal numbers are a proper class of numbers developed by John H. Conway and introduced by Donald Knuth in 1975. They form a proper class into which all ordered fields can be embedded. The approach we take to defining them was first introduced by Hary Goshnor, and is based on the conception of a "sign expansion" of a surreal number. We define the surreals as ordinal-indexed sequences of ` 1o ` and ` 2o ` , analagous to Goshnor's ` ( - ) ` and ` ( + ) ` . After introducing this definition, we will abstract away from it using axioms that Norman Alling developed in "Foundations of Analysis over Surreal Number Fields." This is done in an effort to be agnostic towards the exact implementation of surreals. (Contributed by Scott Fenton, 9-Jun-2011.)

blocks.name: df-slt
blocks.content: Next, we introduce surreal less-than, a comparison relationship over the surreals by lexicographically ordering them. (Contributed by Scott Fenton, 9-Jun-2011.)
blocks.origin:
axiom df-slt(setvar s0, setvar s1, setvar s2, setvar s3) {
  |- wceq(cslt, copab(s0, s1, wa(wa(wcel(cv(s0), csur), wcel(cv(s1), csur)), wrex(s2, con0, wa(wral(s3, cv(s2), wceq(cfv(cv(s0), cv(s3)), cfv(cv(s1), cv(s3)))), wbr(cfv(cv(s0), cv(s2)), ctp(cop(c1o, emptycls), cop(c1o, c2o), cop(emptycls, c2o)), cfv(cv(s1), cv(s2))))))))
  -| diffss(s0, s1)
  -| diffss(s0, s2)
  -| diffss(s0, s3)
  -| diffss(s1, s2)
  -| diffss(s1, s3)
  -| diffss(s2, s3)
}

blocks.name: df-bday
blocks.content: Finally, we introduce the birthday function. This function maps each surreal to an ordinal. In our implementation, this is the domain of the sign function. The important properties of this function are established later. (Contributed by Scott Fenton, 11-Jun-2011.)

blocks.name: elno
blocks.content: Membership in the surreals. (Shortened proof on 2012-Apr-14, SF). (Contributed by Scott Fenton, 11-Jun-2011.)
blocks.origin:
thm elno(setvar s0, class c0) {
  |- wb(wcel(c0, csur), wrex(s0, con0, wf(c0, cv(s0), cpr(c1o, c2o))))
  -| diffsc(s0, c0)
} = {
  pm5.21nii(wcel(c0, csur), wrex(s0, con0, wf(c0, cv(s0), cpr(c1o, c2o))), wcel(c0, universe))
  elex(c0, csur)
  rexlimiva(s0, con0, wf(c0, cv(s0), cpr(c1o, c2o)), wcel(c0, universe))
  ancoms(wcel(cv(s0), con0), wf(c0, cv(s0), cpr(c1o, c2o)), wcel(c0, universe))
  fex(c0, cv(s0), cpr(c1o, c2o), con0)
  elab2g(hs0, c0, universe, csur, wrex(s0, con0, wf(c0, cv(s0), cpr(c1o, c2o))), wrex(s0, con0, wf(cv(hs0), cv(s0), cpr(c1o, c2o))))
  rexbidv(s0, con0, wceq(cv(hs0), c0), wf(cv(hs0), cv(s0), cpr(c1o, c2o)), wf(c0, cv(s0), cpr(c1o, c2o)))
  feq1(cv(hs0), c0, cv(s0), cpr(c1o, c2o))
  df-no(hs0, s0)
  diff.wcel.s(s0, c0, universe)
  diff.universe.s(s0)
  diff.hs0.c(c0)
  diff.hs0.w(wrex(s0, con0, wf(c0, cv(s0), cpr(c1o, c2o))))
  diff.wceq.s(s0, cv(hs0), c0)
  diff.cv.s(s0, hs0)
  diffss.ex(s0, hs0)
  diff.hs0.s(s0)
}

thm nofv(class c0, class c1) {

  pm2.1(wcel(c1, cdm(c0)))
  orim12d(wcel(c0, csur), wn(wcel(c1, cdm(c0))), wcel(c1, cdm(c0)), wceq(cfv(c0, c1), emptycls), wo(wceq(cfv(c0, c1), c1o), wceq(cfv(c0, c1), c2o)))
  a1i(wcel(c0, csur), wi(wn(wcel(c1, cdm(c0))), wceq(cfv(c0, c1), emptycls)))
  ndmfv(c1, c0)
  syl2anc(wcel(c0, csur), wi(wcel(c1, cdm(c0)), wo(wceq(cfv(c0, c1), c1o), wceq(cfv(c0, c1), c2o))), wfun(c0), wss(crn(c0), cpr(c1o, c2o)))
  nofun(c0)
  norn(c0)
  syl6ib(wa(wfun(c0), wss(crn(c0), cpr(c1o, c2o))), wcel(c1, cdm(c0)), wo(wceq(cfv(c0, c1), c1o), wceq(cfv(c0, c1), c2o)), wcel(cfv(c0, c1), cpr(c1o, c2o)))
  impancom(wfun(c0), wss(crn(c0), cpr(c1o, c2o)), wcel(c1, cdm(c0)), wcel(cfv(c0, c1), cpr(c1o, c2o)))
